      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The moisture prevents browning because water has a very high boiling point of 100°C (212°F), and the Maillard reaction requires the surface temperature to reach at least 140°C (284°F) to get going. As long as water is present on the crust, it absorbs the oven's heat to turn into steam, keeping the surface temperature stuck right around 100°C. Since the reaction can't happen below that threshold, the bread stays pale. It's not just about the heat source; it's about the thermodynamics of evaporation acting as a heat sink.\n\nOnce you introduce that steam burst, you're essentially creating a temporary environment where the dough surface is humid, allowing the bread to rise (oven spring) without the crust hardening too soon. As the steam eventually dissipates, the surface temperature spikes above the 140°C mark, and the Maillard reaction finally kicks into high gear. It's a perfect example of how controlling the environment is just as important as controlling the heat itself.\n\nI know it can be confusing without the goblin context, but think of it like this: if you try to cook a meal in a room full of fog,",
